// Time line here

// created from :: https://archive.is/8ZseW
//              :: https://archive.is/uyw71


1970 -- Bell Labs (AT&T) created C language to implement a portable Operating System (Ken Thompson, Dennis Ritchie, (one more person))

1971 -- first edition of UNIX comes out
1972 -- Dennis Ritchie rewrites B and calls it C

1975 -- Bourne Shell is born

1977 -- Berkeley Software design releases BSD

1981 -- fall of Massachusetts Institute of Technology Artificial Intelligence Lab Hacker Community
1984 -- Richard M Stallman quits job at Massachusetts Institute of Technology to work on GNU (Why?)

1985 -- RMS starts work on EMACS

1986 -- the FSF is created

1989 -- release of GNU
     --  release of GNU GPLv1

1991 -- Linus Torvalds develops a 'free' kernel called Linux

1992 -- The 'Gang of Four' develops XFree86
1993 -- Ian Murdock (the spelling may be wrong) starts the Debian Project

1994 -- Apache group is formed, marking the start apache project
1995 -- first RedHat Linux distribution
1996 -- start of the KDE project using a non-free library, Qt

1997 -- Miguel de Icaza and Federico Mena starts the GNOME project

1998 -- Netscape releases its browsers source code, marking the start of Mozilla project
     -- The term Open Source is coined

2002 --	Blender	Formerly proprietary software, released as open source in 2002 after a crowdfunding campaign

December 2003 -- Linux kernel 2.6 released

2005 --	Git	Created by Linux founder Linus Torvalds (World's most popular distributed revision control system)

2013 --	Firefox OS	Mobile phone operating system, released by Mozilla Foundation	
2013 May -- Android	Overtakes iOS to become most popular tablet operating system[6]	

2013 September -- SteamOS	Valve Corporation's new Linux-based operating system for its Steambox consoles, intended to promote Linux gaming and spread Linux adoption in the high-end video game sector